metadata.name: Secunda #74
Shattered Obelisks #41
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

@abakshonokoleg

metadata.name: Abstract Hedonism #42
metadata.description:
Abstraction is the beauty of pure geometry and mathematics.

That project was inspired by fathers of minimalism and suprematism, such as the : El Lissitzky, Kazimir Malevich, Pit Mondrian, Paul Klee, etc.

My main goal was to learn how to work with Perlin noise, implement it in different formats and compositions.

Project contains:

•Various formats and orientations of the canvas: from 100 to 1900 pixels
•Carefully selected color palettes with rare BLACK ones
•Fully random animation
•Press "s" to save .png


Made in P5.js by @Georginerous

metadata.name: Unstable Anticipation #135
metadata.description:
Minimal poster prints of blocks in motion.

Varying block arrangements fall from the canvas's top and interact with pegs near the bottom. After the animation completes, the scene is redrawn with a halftone pattern.

Matter JS is used to calculate the physics.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px

Features
* The length of the simulation
* Number, size, and position of the pegs
* Halftone grid size
* Varying amount of roughness for distorted halftone shapes
* Shape arrangement and composition
* 60/40% Color or monochrome

Copyright (c) 2022 Matt Perkins, hello@mattperkins.me, @nudoru on Twitter. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: GPT-3 and me (free companion mint) #74
metadata.description: Free companion piece to my first Fx(text) article! I have never coded a single line of Javascript in my entire life, yet GPT-3 was able to write the code for this work via my inputs. To read the full article visit: https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/gpt-3-and-me:-a-generative-coding-study

metadata.name: Geode #150
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #39
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Pinceau #4
metadata.description:
An examination of using generative brush strokes to emulate real life paintings.

The result of each output is determined by a number of factors:
- selection from 21 different palettes
- brush transparency levels
- scale factor 
- "chaos level" - determines how far off the given path any the brush strokes of any given piece decide to go.

More info and additional test mints can be found in this thread:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1469083325881106440

metadata.name: Mount Doodle #135
metadata.description:
Tried my best to make every doodle aesthetically pleasing to the eyes.
However, just like nature, beauty often lies in imperfections. :)

Made with p5.js.
Primary split 5% with The Processing Foundation.

Keys
- 1: view 1000px png (Default)
- 2: download 2000px png
- 4: download 4000px png
- 8: download 8000px png
- s: save the image as PNG

When downloading higher resolution pngs, it might take several seconds to redraw the whole image. Download will start immediately after redrawing is completed. Please bear with the slow rendering.
